track_notes: This was a very long hike, because my planned entrance to the power line road was blocked by a locked gate so I hiked in.  You can probably access this road from other ways (perhaps from Oracle Rd), and drive in much closer.  Note that I intentionally came in from this side since it is on State Trust Land, which requires a permit but otherwise is allowed; the other side of the mountain appears to be surrounded by private property.  The bushwhack portion of this hike is dense desert vegetation which means you are often placing your foot in places that you cant see.  Extreme caution is advised.  My down route was better than the up route and if I do this again I would take that approach.  The top is a pile of boulders but plenty of space to put up an antenna and spectacular views.
track_title: Tortilla Benchmark via Power Line Road

track_notes: This track is the route to drive from Hwy 79 to the parking area. The turnoff from Hwy 79 is at GPS 32.62818, -111.00227. Follow the track about 5.4 miles. The roads are good for the most part. Park at the giant silver power line towers at GPS 32.59770, -111.05091 and begin your hike. See my other tracks for the ascent and descent. You must display a valid  AZ State Land Department Recreational Permit Parking Pass on your dashboard.
track_title: W7A/PN-049 TORTILLA BENCHMARK DRIVE FROM HWY 79

track_notes: This is a decent bushwhack if you wear gaiters and heavy duty trousers to protect yourself from cactus, and watch where you step. Park in the area of a crossroads by the big silver high voltage power line towers at GPS 32.59770, -111.05091. The road further south is too dicey to get closer. Hike down the road and crawl under a barb-wire fence at GPS 32.59408, -111.05094. This route follows ridge lines up to the summit. There is a summit marker and a summit register bottle is located in a cairn at the high point.

For the descent I decided to follow a trail that leads to the West from the summit and see where it went. I lost the trail and bushwhacked back to where I ascended. I don’t see any advantage to using this track. The track for the ascent is shorter.
